WERN warehouse analysis

2023-07-18

Overview

Updates to previous analysis:

  • Changed the race categories to White/Black/Hispanic/Other
  • Combined the size categories 1 to 9, 10 to 49, and 50 to 99 into category, 1 to 99
    • It is possible that 50 to 99 is really a different category than than the other two, but I’m not sure it it’s odd to separate it from the others
  • Classified any warehouse that served customers at home as B2C even if it also served other businesses
    • Not sure if this was right choice…
  • Added the following controls:
    • Permanent employment status
    • Union representation


There are a few things to keep in mind:

  • Sample:
    • Hourly warehouse workers
    • I dropped those who report identifying as non-binary, as there were only a couple in the warehouse sample and this made it difficult to perform an intersectional analysis
  • Method:
    • Simple OLS with standard errors that account for survey weights
  • Significance levels are likely to change as we add or remove controls and toss out certain observations
  • Because these models contain multiple dummy variables and interactions, proceed with caution when interpreting the coefficient estimates. It is usually much more straightforward to look at a visual, which is why I included some graphs. Let me know if you want to see other particular visuals.
  • The reference levels used in regression analyses are:
    • Race: White
    • Gender: Male
    • Warehouse type: B2B
    • Warehouse size: 100 to 499
  • Earnings and tenure are treated here as continuous but are really binned variables. Hence, the values themselves aren’t very meaningful–the levels are.
  • The wage measure has a lot of missingness, so for now I am using an annual earnings measure (which isn’t great)


Main takeaways:

  • TBD

[Old takeways:]

  • Women of color, especially black women, tend to respond more negatively to most questions. It is safe to say black women are marginalized on most measures and usually to a significant degree.
    • Black men appear to diverge from black women on most items. If we didn’t perform an intersectional analysis, it is unclear how much different white and black workers would appear (though I haven’t tested this speculation yet.)
  • Those who work in business to consumer warehouses, a proxy for e-commerce fulfillment, tend to respond more negatively to most questions. This provides support for the assertation that demand volatility and business competition make fulfillment centers especially difficult workplaces.
    • I haven’t paid much mind to size, but smaller workplaces appear better, further suggesting that fulfillment centers are particularly tough.


Questions to discuss/next steps:

  • Besides the main takeaways above, what other through lines, stylized facts, suprises, puzzles, etc. might we convey at AOM?
  • For which variables do we want to compare hourly and salaried workers? Is there any reason to keep them in sample and control for pay type?
  • What are other possible control variables?
    • There are other demographic variables, like marital status, which we might debate whether to include.
  • I want to create a warehouse-specific measure of a bad schedule that is more about long hours than instability per se.
  • The “Don’t know” response option is creating a lot of problems. What should be do about it? Keep in? Drop observations with it? Impute?
  • Look at the relationship between technology or building size in a) surveillance and b) work intensity
